  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Providing Quality Integrated Primary and Reproductive Healthcare services to conflict affected IDPs in Monguno,  Bama, Jere and Maiduguri LGA, Borno State</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">By building and consolidating on the gains achieved by the IRC under the NHF/OCHA 90 day funding in response to the influx of Internally Displaced Persons (IDP) into MMC (Maiduguri) and Monguno local government areas (LGA) in Borno state, the IRC seeks to strengthen its primary and reproductive healthcare services for internally displaced persons and host community members through direct treatment at IRC facilities. Through this OCHA-supported action, the IRC will further strengthen the provision of health care services by providing primary and reproductive care at existing static health facilities at the Stadium IDP Camp in Maiduguri and in Fulatari Camp at Monguno. 

The IRC will continue, under this action to run its integrated comprehensive, Reproductive health clinic targeting adolescent girls, women of child bearing age, and pregnant and lactating women (PLW). The IRC will provide clinical management of rape for all identified cases of gender based violence, (GBV) ante-natal services, post-natal services, and syndromic management of sexually transmitted infection (STIs) services.

Through the IRC&#x2019;s established referral pathway and mechanism, which includes an established ambulance service, with payment of hospital cost for all referred IDPs and host community members and the existing referral linkage to the University of Maiduguri Teaching hospital, which has now expanded to include the States Specialist Hospital, Umaru Shehu Hospital and Mamman Shuwa Memorial Hospital. The IRC will further plug the referral gap under this action.

The IRC, in the case of an epidemic will adapt its programming to effectively respond by leveraging on the existing community structures and propositioned medicines and products.</narrative>
  </description>
